Enough has been said about the food so I'll talk about seating. Some of the two-seater tables are in a pretty tight row. This is fine, but if you want a romantic, quiet dinner with personal conversation then this might not always be the right environment, especially if the people next to you are inebriated and drunkenly tipping over into your space, as was my experience. I was kind of amused but others might be bothered. Other tables are more private so try to get seated there if you care. We had the Roast Maine Lobster, the Mousseline Wrapped Pork Tenderloin, the Seared Filet of Beef with Yukon Potatoes, and the Black Pepper and Rosemary Crusted Tuna. Of those, I thought the Pork dish was the best.

My husband brought us here for our fourth anniversary on Thursday (Halloween ) and what a treat. The staff was friendly and attentive. The food was delicious. The entree's were flavorful and I certainly enjoyed the cheese course. To top a wonderful dinner we ordered their soufflés and they were remarkable. The portions (depending on what was ordered) are very decent in size. Perhaps not the best environment for little ones but I do hope to bring my son here as me matures. Thank you to Gary Danko for such a wonderful experience.

Gary Danko is hands down my favorite restaurant in San Francisco. I have been here four or five times over the last few years for special occasions and it is worth every penny. If you are looking for fine dining but actually want to recognize what the dishes on the menu are, this place is for you. The first time we came, we did 5 courses each. We left and we're absolutely stuffed (like barely breathing), so ever since we've opted for four. I'll start with the service: First off, I'm a sucker for bread and butter and love any restaurant that comes and refills my bread plate when they see it's empty. Secondly, when you get up and go to the bathroom, they come and put a cover over your food so it stays warm. If that's not great service then I don't know what is. Lastly, the staff is incredibly friendly, taking the time to answer questions and check in throughout the meal. When I dine there I truly feel like I am treated like royalty, which is nice when you're dropping a lot of money. Then there's the food. I could go on and on but instead I'll share my dishes from my most recent visit: Appetizer- the risotto. I'm not sure if this changes with the seasons because I typically go in July every year, but it usually has rock shrimp, crab and vegetables in it and is delightful. Fish: roast main lobster with potato purée. Hands down my favorite dish with the exception of dessert, which we'll get to soon. Meat: seared filet of beef. Good steak. Probably my least favorite of the bunch but not because it's not good, the other dishes are just spectacular. Cheese: they roll out a cart and let you select a few. Dessert: warm Louisiana butter cake. This is no joke. My boyfriend and I literally talk about this more often than people should. Hands down the best dessert I've ever had in my life. I would pay $50 for this alone. When you leave, they give you a treat to go, which is a nice touch. Overall, you'll spend a lot of money but it is so worth it.

Love how you can pick any 3 items from the menu for their 3 course meal. You can actually do 3 mains! I had the oysters and crab quinoa salad. Both of which I would avoid and the reason why I did not give this place 5 stars. The salad was bland and although well presented and plated, did nothing to enhance the flavors of it's ingredients. The oysters were marinated in a sauce which caused it to lose all oyster freshness. Please avoid. Seafood we had were scallops and lobster. The scallops were excellent. seared just right with a soft center and light sauce to complement. The lobster was a tap over cooked for my taste - however, I've been told that I eat things too rare. Otherwise the lobster was delicious. For mains we had bison and steak. The bison was FANTASTIC! please order! Grilled just right with a soft pink center without it being raw or cold. Also had a unique kind of german pasta that had a soft texture (but somehow not mushy) that paired very well. The steak had a foie gras sauce that I did not appreciate, however the cooking was just as good as the bison. Dessert was chocolate bar. I loved the peanut flavors with dank af chocolate! If you're adverse to bitter chocolate then skip. As it was my birthday they also gave us a complimentary fruity sorbet/mousse and a selection of small sweets. Sorbet/mousse was refreshing, but a tap too sweet for my taste. I'd pass on the sweeties. Service was stellar as well! Very well done. Only additional point of improvement would be the interior decor. Doesn't ring of high class eating.

Believe what you see with your eyes ,the culinary experience without a doubt and entertaining and appetite opening event. Very cozy interior, great customer service and food to die for. No wonder they have so many good reviews can't wait to go back for the waiter that ordered for me thank you so much bon appétit

Finally!!! After years of waiting, I finally got a chance to get reservations for this restaurant. My BFF and I planned a birthday trip to celebrate my milestone and we decided to hit up wine country and SF. We had made reservations 5 months in advance with careful planning. A credit card is needed to make reservations. The only reservation available for the day we wanted was 9pm. Damn that's late! We played dress up and took an uber from our hotel and arrived early enough to ensure we checked in. We were welcomed and promptly sat at a cute little booth on the left side of the restaurant. The sitting area is tiny with about 10-ish tables. Our booth was a little funky as we were sitting side by side and looking out towards the other tables. There was also another table next to us with the same sitting situation. The tables are super close together so get cozy with your neighbors! We decided to do the 3- course tasting menu since we were eating all day. We were going to share plates as well so we chose different items. There is a 3, 4, or 5 course available from $87-$124. We both decided on cocktails to start. I opted for a glass of prosecco. They offer a little taste before they pour you a glass. For the courses, you get to select courses from any of the categories. You can choose all entrees, all starters, all desserts, or mix and match. We were offered comped bread and butter as we wait. We chose to share the following: -branzini: loved the softness of the fish and the crispy skin. Yum! -roasted Maine lobster: super buttery and left me wanting more. My fave of all of the nights tasting. I would order 3 of this for my 3 course! -seared filet of beef: my entree was amazing! So tender and flavorful. I engulfed that baby up within minutes! -loin of lamb: served rare so if you want it to be cooked more make sure you let them know! Even if you ask for med rare you should really ask about preparations. It was delicious though. -chocolate soufflé: so so good, but rich! -warm butter cake: my BFF loved his dessert. I'm more of a chocolate fan so I defer to my soufflé. We also ordered coffees with our desserts. Since I was celebrating my milestone, I was also given a chocolate torte cake with a happy birthday decorated on the plate and a candle. Lastly, we were given a plate of petite desserts compliments of the chef! As a departing gift we were also given pineapple upside down cakes for our breakfast the next morning. How awesome is that! One of the best dining experiences I've had, and looking forward to taking my husband on a special occasion when we come back to the Bay Area! Tip: Def make your res as soon as possible to get a reasonable dinner time!

Finally, after hearing so much about Gary Danko I had the chance to come dine in this elegant restaurant to celebrate my partner's birthday. We made reservations 3 weeks in advance where the staff informed us what available dates and times they had and they even called us a day before our reservation as a friendly reminder. If you're worried about parking, don't be. There are plenty of options around the area with their own valet parking for $20, a parking garage up the block, or metered street parking good for up to 4 hours until 7pm. we were lucky to have found metered parking down the block in a heavy traffic area. Upon arrival we3 were greeted by the host and seated promptly. Our waiter asked if we've dine at Gary Danko before and we replied that we have not and he kindly went through all of our options and answered every questions we had. You basically choose your preferred amount of courses and pick any item on the menu. If you chose a 3 course you can grab 3 desserts or 3 entrees etc you're not limited to getting 1 appetizer, 1 entree and 1 dessert you can choose whatever you like. Our waiter also stated that they don't recommend all meat/poultry dishes for your courses but, if we wanted to, they won't decline to give it to you. Food review: I went with the 3 course meal and my partner with 4 courses. We were also given a lot of free stuff (along with every diner in the restaurant) compliments from the chef. We were given a pea soup appetizer, for dessert we were given assortment of chocolate and sweets, and a parting cake gift. My selection consisted of: Glazed oyster with osetra caviar with zucchini pearls, leeks and lettuce cream, Roast Maine lobster with potato puree, chanterelle mushrooms, corn and tarragon, and Herb Crusted Loin of Lamb with Summer Vegetable Tian and Polenta. They were all done very well and I would recommend any of these dishes all the meats were cooked perfctly medium rare and just melted in my mouth like butter. They were pretty small in portions and wondered if i would be full and if I made the right choice with a 3 course meal but, luckily the loin of lamb did the job! My partner ordered the Ahi Tuna, Seared foie gras, with caramelized onions, and cherry, Lemon pepper duck breast with duck hash, bacon braised endive and port glazed cherries, and the Trio of Creme brulee. All were done amazingly and much heartier than my choices. The only dish that was underwhelming for me was the Ahi Tuna, Where the cumin was really present and the lime juice made the dish really acidic as well. The old fashion I ordered was perfectly mad and one of the best I've had and the Moscow Mule was plenty strong. End food review The staff were all exquisite and attentive and could be the best service I've had in a restaurant. There will be two main impressions people will have about Gary Danko the Restaurant either you will love it or you'll think it's just okay. I loved my experienced here but, i know many friends who thought it was okay. Our waiter gave us a little tip after bringing us the bill, If they're full, you can always come by and sit at the bar without reservations. You will be able to order food a la carte and dessert which was great to know for the future. After picking up the bill our waiter also asked us if we need validation, if we used their valet or if he could call a cab for us which was great for them to offer!

One of the best services I've experienced in a long time! Came here with my date for my birthday and thoroughly enjoyed the experience. Venue: slightly dark, golden interior with large flower accents without looking too gaudy. Service: the staff are super attentive of each customer as soon as you walk through the front door; you feel fancy schmancy because of how well they treat you. They keep watch of your pace as you work through your meal and I don't think I felt like I was waiting around for someone to pick up our finished plates or waiting for the next course. They also were good in refilling wine and water glasses (think my boyfriend refilled my glass only once). Food: you can choose 3 courses ($89), 4 courses ($109), or 5 courses ($128 per person) and can literally choose any items for your courses. So if you are a dessert person, they'll allow you to choose all desserts. They'll also let you know if certain combinations might be too filling and such (and thank goodness for that), especially if you are ordering 5 courses. -- Dungeness Crab Salad with Melons, Cucumbers, Roasted Eggplant and Thai Mango Dressing - great, light refreshing start. Funny how I'm not a big fan of either eggplant or cucumber but I didn't mind it in this dish because of the decent amount of crab and the sweet, tangy dressing -- Poached Farm Egg "Carbonara" with Braised Bacon and Brioche - one of the richer small dishes. It's smaller too (finished in 2-3 bites) but very tasty! Bacon wasn't too salty and the brioche had a good level of sweetness to cut through the smokey bacon and rich egg yolk. Sauce was thick and creamy but portion-wise worked for me. -- Seared Scallop with Butternut Fondue, Braised Leeks, Carrot-Parsnip Purée, Pickled Root Vegetables and Sage - scallops were a decent size and seared well (without overcooking). I was a fan of the carrot-parsnip puree, but everything else on the plate seemed like a throw-away / wasn't too special. Couldn't taste the fondue since it was a thin layer on the plate and the leeks were just... there. Of the dishes I had that night, this was the weakest (out of some very outstanding ones). -- Juniper Crusted Bison with King Trumpet Mushrooms, Cipollini Onions and Herb Spätzle - first time trying bison (cooked rare per standards) and surprisingly finished the whole portion (and it's a decent portion for a 5 course meal). Think rib-eye flavor-wise, but slightly chewier without it being a turnoff. Mushrooms worked well by adding an earthy taste to the dish. The herb spätzle was amazing- soft but not overcooked, and very homey flavor-wise. Would recommend as a large dish to your meal. -- Grand Marnier Soufflé with Raspberry Sorbet and Two Sauces - my boyfriend booked this dinner because of their famous souffle, and this was probably my favorite of all time. They are better known for their chocolate one, but the Grand Marnier souffle was awesome too. Most souffles have a texture like a light sponge cake, but this one almost had the texture of a marshmallow. Still had a sweet, citrusy grand marnier flavor, accented by the raspberry sorbet, raspberry sauce and light passion-fruit sauce. Highlight of my meal and highly recommend as a dessert. For my birthday, they also served a mini lemon cake with strawberry slices and lemon preserve and cream cheese frosting. This is in addition to some petit fours they give at the end of the meal and the pineapple cake they give to everyone when you leave. My boyfriend had the glazed oysters (his favorite), risotto, branzini, quail, and the cheese course. All together, the meal came out to $400-$450 with wine. To summarize, the service is what made this place excellent. Food, while not the absolute best meal I've had, was also great enough that, along with impeccable service, would make me recommend people to visit Gary Danko at least once.

    Gary Danko is hands down my favorite restaurant in San Francisco. I have been here four or five times over the last few years for special occasions and it is worth every penny. If you are looking for fine dining but actually want to recognize what the dishes on the menu are, this place is for you.

    The first time we came, we did 5 courses each. We left and we're absolutely stuffed (like barely breathing), so ever since we've opted for four.

    I'll start with the service:
    First off, I'm a sucker for bread and butter and love any restaurant that comes and refills my bread plate when they see it's empty.
    Secondly, when you get up and go to the bathroom, they come and put a cover over your food so it stays warm. If that's not great service then I don't know what is.
    Lastly, the staff is incredibly friendly, taking the time to answer questions and check in throughout the meal. When I dine there I truly feel like I am treated like royalty, which is nice when you're dropping a lot of money.

    Then there's the food. I could go on and on but instead I'll share my dishes from my most recent visit:
    Appetizer- the risotto. I'm not sure if this changes with the seasons because I typically go in July every year, but it usually has rock shrimp, crab and vegetables in it and is delightful.
    Fish: roast main lobster with potato purée. Hands down my favorite dish with the exception of dessert, which we'll get to soon.
    Meat: seared filet of beef. Good steak. Probably my least favorite of the bunch but not because it's not good, the other dishes are just spectacular.
    Cheese: they roll out a cart and let you select a few.
    Dessert: warm Louisiana butter cake. This is no joke. My boyfriend and I literally talk about this more often than people should. Hands down the best dessert I've ever had in my life. I would pay $50 for this alone.

    When you leave, they give you a treat to go, which is a nice touch. Overall, you'll spend a lot of money but it is so worth it.

    Seafood we had were scallops and lobster. The scallops were excellent. seared just right with a soft center and light sauce to complement. The lobster was a tap over cooked for my taste - however, I've been told that I eat things too rare. Otherwise the lobster was delicious.

    For mains we had bison and steak. The bison was FANTASTIC! please order! Grilled just right with a soft pink center without it being raw or cold. Also had a unique kind of german pasta that had a soft texture (but somehow not mushy) that paired very well.  The steak had a foie gras sauce that I did not appreciate, however the cooking was just as good as the bison.

    Dessert was chocolate bar. I loved the peanut flavors with dank af chocolate! If you're adverse to bitter chocolate then skip. As it was my birthday they also gave us a complimentary fruity sorbet/mousse and a selection of small sweets.  Sorbet/mousse was refreshing, but a tap too sweet for my taste. I'd pass on the sweeties.

    Service was stellar as well! Very well done. Only additional point of improvement would be the interior decor. Doesn't ring of high class eating.

    Finally!!! After years of waiting, I finally got a chance to get reservations for this restaurant. My BFF and I planned a birthday trip to celebrate my milestone and we decided to hit up wine country and SF. We had made reservations 5 months in advance with careful planning. A credit card is needed to make reservations. The only reservation available for the day we wanted was 9pm. Damn that's late!

    We played dress up and took an uber from our hotel and arrived early enough to ensure we checked in. We were welcomed and promptly sat at a cute little booth on the left side of the restaurant. The sitting area is tiny with about 10-ish tables. Our booth was a little funky as we were sitting side by side and looking out towards the other tables. There was also another table next to us with the same sitting situation. The tables are super close together so get cozy with your neighbors!

    We decided to do the 3- course tasting menu since we were eating all day. We were going to share plates as well so we chose different items. There is a 3, 4, or 5 course available from $87-$124. We both decided on cocktails to start. I opted for a glass of prosecco. They offer a little taste before they pour you a glass. For the courses, you get to select courses from any of the categories. You can choose all entrees, all starters, all desserts, or mix and match. We were offered comped bread and butter as we wait.

    We chose to share the following:
    -branzini: loved the softness of the fish and the crispy skin. Yum!
    -roasted Maine lobster: super buttery and left me wanting more. My fave of all of the nights tasting. I would order 3 of this for my 3 course!
    -seared filet of beef: my entree was amazing! So tender and flavorful. I engulfed that baby up within minutes!
    -loin of lamb: served rare so if you want it to be cooked more make sure you let them know! Even if you ask for med rare you should really ask about preparations. It was delicious though.
    -chocolate soufflé: so so good, but rich!
    -warm butter cake: my BFF loved his dessert. I'm more of a chocolate fan so I defer to my soufflé.

    We also ordered coffees with our desserts. Since I was celebrating my milestone, I was also given a chocolate torte cake with a happy birthday decorated on the plate and a candle. Lastly, we were given a plate of petite desserts compliments of the chef!

    As a departing gift we were also given pineapple upside down cakes for our breakfast the next morning. How awesome is that!

    One of the best dining experiences I've had, and looking forward to taking my husband on a special occasion when we come back to the Bay Area!

    Tip: Def make your res as soon as possible to get a reasonable dinner time!

    Finally, after hearing so much about Gary Danko I had the chance to come dine in this elegant restaurant to celebrate my partner's birthday.
    We made reservations 3 weeks in advance where the staff informed us what available dates and times they had and they even called us a day before our reservation as a friendly reminder. If you're worried about parking, don't be. There are plenty of options around the area with their own valet parking for $20, a parking garage up the block, or metered street parking good for up to 4 hours until 7pm. we were lucky to have found metered parking down the block in a heavy traffic area.

    Upon arrival we3 were greeted by the host and seated promptly. Our waiter asked if we've dine at Gary Danko before and we replied that we have not and he kindly went through all of our options and answered every questions we had. You basically choose your preferred amount of courses and pick any item on the menu. If you chose a 3 course you can grab 3 desserts or 3 entrees etc you're not limited to getting 1 appetizer, 1 entree and 1 dessert you can choose whatever you like. Our waiter also stated that they don't recommend all meat/poultry dishes for your courses but, if we wanted to, they won't decline to give it to you.

    Food review:

    I went with the 3 course meal and my partner with 4 courses. We were also given a lot of free stuff (along with every diner in the restaurant) compliments from the chef. We were given a pea soup appetizer, for dessert we were given assortment of chocolate and sweets, and a parting cake gift.

    My selection consisted of: Glazed oyster with osetra caviar with zucchini pearls, leeks and lettuce cream, Roast Maine lobster with potato puree, chanterelle mushrooms, corn and tarragon, and Herb Crusted Loin of Lamb with Summer Vegetable Tian and Polenta. They were all done very well and I would recommend any of these dishes all the meats were cooked perfctly medium rare and just melted in my mouth like butter. They were pretty small in portions and wondered if i would be full and if I made the right choice with a 3 course meal but, luckily the loin of lamb did the job!

    My partner ordered the Ahi Tuna, Seared foie gras, with caramelized onions, and cherry, Lemon pepper duck breast with duck hash, bacon braised endive and port glazed cherries, and the Trio of Creme brulee. All were done amazingly and much heartier than my choices. The only dish that was underwhelming for me was the Ahi Tuna, Where the cumin was really present and the lime juice made the dish really acidic as well.

    The old fashion I ordered was perfectly mad and one of the best I've had and the Moscow Mule was plenty strong.

    End food review

    The staff were all exquisite and attentive and could be the best service I've had in a restaurant. There will be two main impressions people will have about Gary Danko the Restaurant either you will love it or you'll think it's just okay. I loved my experienced here but, i know many friends who thought it was okay.

    Our waiter gave us a little tip after bringing us the bill, If they're full, you can always come by and sit at the bar without reservations. You will be able to order food a la carte and dessert which was great to know for the future. After picking up the bill our waiter also asked us if we need validation, if we used their valet or if he could call a cab for us which was great for them to offer!

    11/14/2017

    6 photos

    One of the best services I've experienced in a long time!  Came here with my date for my birthday and thoroughly enjoyed the experience.

    Venue: slightly dark, golden interior with large flower accents without looking too gaudy.  

    Service: the staff are super attentive of each customer as soon as you walk through the front door; you feel fancy schmancy because of how well they treat you.  They keep watch of your pace as you work through your meal and I don't think I felt like I was waiting around for someone to pick up our finished plates or waiting for the next course.  They also were good in refilling wine and water glasses (think my boyfriend refilled my glass only once).  

    Food: you can choose 3 courses ($89), 4 courses ($109), or 5 courses ($128 per person) and can literally choose any items for your courses.  So if you are a dessert person, they'll allow you to choose all desserts.  They'll also let you know if certain combinations might be too filling and such (and thank goodness for that), especially if you are ordering 5 courses.  

    -- Dungeness Crab Salad with Melons, Cucumbers, Roasted Eggplant and Thai Mango Dressing - great, light refreshing start.  Funny how I'm not a big fan of either eggplant or cucumber but I didn't mind it in this dish because of the decent amount of crab and the sweet, tangy dressing

    -- Poached Farm Egg "Carbonara" with Braised Bacon and Brioche - one of the richer small dishes.  It's smaller too (finished in 2-3 bites) but very tasty!  Bacon wasn't too salty and the brioche had a good level of sweetness to cut through the smokey bacon and rich egg yolk.  Sauce was thick and creamy but portion-wise worked for me.

    -- Seared Scallop with Butternut Fondue, Braised Leeks, Carrot-Parsnip Purée, Pickled Root Vegetables and Sage - scallops were a decent size and seared well (without overcooking).  I was a fan of the carrot-parsnip puree, but everything else on the plate seemed like a throw-away / wasn't too special.  Couldn't taste the fondue since it was a thin layer on the plate and the leeks were just... there.  Of the dishes I had that night, this was the weakest (out of some very outstanding ones).

    -- Juniper Crusted Bison with King Trumpet Mushrooms, Cipollini Onions and Herb Spätzle - first time trying bison (cooked rare per standards) and surprisingly finished the whole portion (and it's a decent portion for a 5 course meal).  Think rib-eye flavor-wise, but slightly chewier without it being a turnoff.  Mushrooms worked well by adding an earthy taste to the dish.  The herb spätzle was amazing- soft but not overcooked, and very homey flavor-wise.  Would recommend as a large dish to your meal.  

    -- Grand Marnier Soufflé with Raspberry Sorbet and Two Sauces - my boyfriend booked this dinner because of their famous souffle, and this was probably my favorite of all time.  They are better known for their chocolate one, but the Grand Marnier souffle was awesome too.  Most souffles have a texture like a light sponge cake, but this one almost had the texture of a marshmallow.  Still had a sweet, citrusy grand marnier flavor, accented by the raspberry sorbet, raspberry sauce and light passion-fruit sauce.  Highlight of my meal and highly recommend as a dessert.  

    For my birthday, they also served a mini lemon cake with strawberry slices and lemon preserve and cream cheese frosting.  This is in addition to some petit fours they give at the end of the meal and the pineapple cake they give to everyone when you leave.

    My boyfriend had the glazed oysters (his favorite), risotto, branzini, quail, and the cheese course.  All together, the meal came out to $400-$450 with wine.  

    To summarize, the service is what made this place excellent.  Food, while not the absolute best meal I've had, was also great enough that, along with impeccable service, would make me recommend people to visit Gary Danko at least once.
